UML:TaggedValue.value: The name of the CCTV camera base station which has primary control of the camera (i.e. owns the camera).
The identity of the CCTV camera base station which has primary control of the camera (i.e. owns the camera).
The name of the road operator's control centre (e.g. South East Regional Control Centre) which is associated with the CCTV camera base station that has primary control of the camera.
The identity of the road operator's control centre (e.g. SERCC) which is associated with the CCTV camera base station that has primary control of the camera.
The name of the work group in the control centre which has primary control of the CCTV camera.
The identity of the work group in the control centre which has primary control of the CCTV camera.
The name of the cctv camera list.
The date/time that this version of the CCTV camera list was defined by the supplier. The identity and version of the CCTV camera list are defined by the class stereotype implementation.
Set of preset values that are available for the CCTV camera.
The pan value for the CCTV camera at its minimum pan end stop.
The pan value for the CCTV camera at its maximum pan end stop.
The tilt value for the CCTV camera at its minimum tilt end stop.
The tilt value for the CCTV camera at its maximum tilt end stop.
The zoom value for the CCTV camera at its maximum zoom setting.
The identity of the set of preset CCTV camera values.
The name of the set of preset CCTV camera values.
The level assigned to this video service.
The name assigned to this video service level.
The video compression standard used, e.g. MPEG2, MPEG4.
Texual description of the resolution, e.g. "CIF" (Common Intermediate Format), "SIF" (Source Input Format), etc.
The number of video frames per second on this video service.
The bit rate of this video service level measured in bits per second.
The zoom level beyond which video images for this service level will be blanked.
The URL from where the current video stream from the CCTV camera can be obtained.
The URL from where a sample orientation image for the video service from the CCTV camera can be obtained to assist in identifying camera orientation.
More modern CCTV cameras may be able to pan continuously and hence would not have any end stop pan values.
The identifier assigned to the CCTV camera at its deployed location.

The serial number of the actual CCTV camera equipment installed. When the deployed camera is replaced (e.g. during maintenance) this serial number will change, whereas the camera identification will stay the same.
The date/time that this version of the CCTV camera record was defined. The identity and version of the CCTV camera record are defined by the class stereotype implementation.
A description of the site where the CCTV camera is deployed which is likely to be used by users with local knowledge (e.g. "M4 187/8b St Catherine's Hill").
A description of the site where the CCTV camera is deployed which is likely to be used by users without local knowledge (e.g. "M4 westbound between J20 and J21").

An image content description which may help clients identify camera orientation, e.g. "The carriageway closest to the camera is northbound", or "If the road curves to the left the camera is pointing south".
The type of the CCTV camera.
The height in metres of the CCTV camera head above the roadway.
An indication of whether the CCTV camera is a fixed type or a pan/tilt/zoom type. "True" indicates it is fixed.
An indication of whether the CCTV camera is a static or a mobile type. "True" indicates it is static.
The identifier of the next CCTV camera on the same road relative to the traffic direction on the principle monitored carriageway (there may be multiple next cameras at junctions and slip roads).

The identifier of the previous CCTV camera on the same road relative to the traffic direction on the principle monitored carriageway (there may be multiple previous cameras at junctions and slip roads).
A location (i.e. a point such as a car park exit, a linear section of the road network with specified direction or an area) that the CCTV camera is potentially capable of effectively monitoring.
Name of a nation (e.g. Wales) which is a sub-division of a ISO recognised country.
Name of a police force area.
Name of a road operator control area.
The pan value for the CCTV camera at the top left of the dwell zone.
The tilt value for the CCTV camera at the top left of the dwell zone.
The pan value for the CCTV camera at the bottom right of the dwell zone.
The tilt value for the CCTV camera at the bottom right of the dwell zone.
The pan value for the CCTV camera when pointing true north represented as a 2 byte value.
The tilt value for the CCTV camera when pointing true north represented as a 2 byte value.
The zoom value for the CCTV camera when pointing true north represented as a 2 byte value.
The level assigned to this still image service.
The name assigned to this still image service level.
The zoom level beyond which still images for this service level will be blanked.
The URL from where a sample orientation image for the still image service from the CCTV camera can be obtained to assist in identifying camera orientation.
The URL from where the current still images from the CCTV camera can be obtained.
The level assigned to this video service.
An indication of the current availability of this service from the CCTV camera.
Statement as to whether the current video stream from this service level is broadcastable to the general public.
A reference to a versioned CCTV camera list.
A reference to a record that contains the metadata for a specific camera.
The point in time at which the status of the CCTV camera has been determined.
The current orientation of the camera expressed in terms of a bearing from true north.
The current orientation of the camera expressed in terms of a compass point direction.
A location (i.e. a linear section of the road network with specified direction or an area) that is currently being monitored by the CCTV camera.
The level assigned to this still image service.
An indication of the current availability of this still image service from the CCTV camera.
A statement as to whether the current images from this service level are broadcastable to the general public.
The current availability status of the CCTV camera to be controlled by a client.
The identity of the client which is currently in control of the CCTV camera.
The control privilege level of the client which is currently in control of the CCTV camera.

The group of users to which the client that is currently controlling the CCTV belongs, e.g. national, regional, local authority or metropolitan authority traffic control centre, toll road operator, police, etc.
If the CCTV camera is currently set to a preset this specifies the identifier of that preset (as may have been specified in the CctvSiteTablePublication).
Camera is currently available for control.
Camera is currently blocked by the system from being controlled by anyone (e.g. during camera maintenance).
Control of the CCTV camera is currently assigned to another user/client and therefore control may only be available if the requesting client possesses a higher level control privilege.
Video or still images for this service level are available from the camera.
Video or still images for this service level are unavailable due to a camera fault.
Video or still images from the camera are currently blanked to non priveleged users by the road operator (e.g. during management of an incident).
Video or still images from the camera are currently blanked to non privileged users by the police (e.g. during a serious event handled by police).

Video or still images from the camera are currently blanked to non privileged users by the system (e.g. due to camera zoom levels beyond those permitted for normal access or due to camera pointing in a prohibited direction).
Video or still images from the camera are currently blanked to non privileged users by the system 's administrator (i.e. only those with administrator priveleges have access).
Failure in ability to control CCTV camera.
Not currently in service (e.g. intentionally disconnected or switched off during roadworks).
Power to CCTV camera has failed.
Charge-coupled device black and white imaging camera.
Video camera tube (type of cathode ray tube) that produces colour images.
Video camera tube (type of cathode ray tube) that produces black and white images.
Container package for content model extensions. Each extension should be contained in its own package.
A collection of data relating to the publication of CCTV status information.
Publication of CCTV camera lists providing metadata and status information such as fault and availability status for individual deployed CCTV cameras.
A collection of lists of enumeration values used throughout the CCTV extensions of the DATEX 2 model.
Specification of who and/or which camera base station has primary responsibility for control of the CCTV camera.

A list of CCTV cameras deployed on the road network or part of the road network, optionally relating to a specific area, where each list entry identifies metadata relating to an individual CCTV camera.
A publication defining one or more lists of CCTV cameras deployed on the road network where each entry on a list identifies metadata relating to an individual CCTV camera.
Details of the control aspects of the CCTV camera that are relevant for a client.
Limits imposed on the control of the CCTV camera.

Reference to a set of preset values for the CCTV camera, normally maintained by the base station, each corresponding to a defined pointing direction and zoom level which may be selectable by a controlling client.
Details of the video service available from the CCTV camera.
A record containing the metadata relating to a specific CCTV camera.
Geographic area to which the CCTV camera list relates

A viewing zone in which the CCTV camera is not allowed to stop, identified by a virtual rectangular area defined by a top left and bottom right position. Normally the camera is automatically moved through this zone expeditiously.
The pan, tilt and zoom values for the CCTV camera when pointing true north.
Details of a still image service available from the CCTV camera.
Details of the current status of a video service available from a CCTV camera.
A publication defining the current status of one or more CCTV cameras.
The current status of a CCTV camera.
Details of the current status of a still image service available from the CCTV camera.
Details of the current control status of the CCTV camera by a client.
Types of availability of CCTV camera control.
Types of availability of video or still images from a CCTV camera.
Types of faults relating to CCTV cameras.
